Configurable state machine Instruction now locked as View Only and anomaly correction – Sts_StateTime and Sts_StepTime not counting time in current state and current step. ============================================================ Instruction Overview: ----- The configurable state model instruction provides a command and status interface for modular code objects. This allows user to develop a control strategy without requiring knowledge of where the physical signals are sourced, making the logic I/O agnostic.
Configurable state model capabilities and limitations · States are either commanded or static. Commanded states are reached by issuing state commands. The instruction remains in a static state until a command is received, or an exception occurs. · State 0 is the Initial State. The Initial state is treated as a commanded state, and is triggered on first program scan or when leaving Out of Service Mode. · At least 1 state must be, and as many as 31 states can be configured. · States 1 through 16 can be configured from the HMI Faceplate · Each enabled state has a list of allowed transition target states, used to validate transition requests. If the transition from State A to State B is not allowed by this transition list, the transition request is ignored. · A commanded state transitions to a configured target state upon completion of the state’s associated automation sequence. · Each state has a permissive input bit that must be set to transition to that state. · A sequence step value can be initialized on each state transition. · Override and Fault Exception Modes may have associated states. If such exception states are not configured, the exception modes do not trigger transitions, but do prevent commands from doing so while the modes are active. · Out of Service is the highest-priority exception state, always associated with State 0.
Object Ownership · Under normal operating conditions, the raM_Opr_CfgStateModel is commanded either by the application logic (Program Ownership) or from the HMI (Operator Ownership). · The Program can acquire ownership from the Operator on request, unless the Operator has applied an Ownership Lock. Likewise, the Operator can acquire Ownership from the Program unless the Program has applied an Ownership Lock. · Both Program and Operator can relinquish Ownership to the other whether Locked or not. · The Program/Operator ownership model is provided by the embedded raM_Opr_CmdSrc instruction. · Ownership model can be changed offline, or online in program mode. · One of five ownership models can be selected, determining the rules of obtaining and retaining ownership: 0 = Normal Ownership: Operator / Operator Lock / Program / Program Lock 1 = No Operator Lock Allowed 2 = Maintained Program / Operator Ownership Request 3 = Program Owner Only 4 = Operator Owner Only
Exception Modes · Provided by the raM_Opr_CmdSrc instruction, exception modes are indicated by status flags in the raM_Opr_CfgStateModel tag. · Concurrent requests for multiple Exception Modes will result in the Mode of highest requested priority taking effect, with the lower priority requests being ignored until the higher request is removed.
The defined exception modes (highest to lowest): 1. Out of Service · The module entity is not available for use. No transitions are performed. · Out_eState, Sts_eStep, Sts_StateTime, and Sts_StepTime outputs are set to zero. · The raM_Opr_CfgStateModel enters Out of Service mode when logic preceding the AOI is false (LD) or the EnableIn pin is 0 (FBD). · The Maintenance Owner can take the raM_Opr_CfgStateModel out of service, and return the raM_Opr_CfgStateModel to service via HMI command. 2. Maintenance · The module entity is under maintenance control, allowing expanded access to state transition control for troubleshooting purposes. · Unless Sts_OoS is set, all state transitions are triggered manually via HMI faceplate. · Operator and Program state requests are ignored. · State permissive inputs and valid transition table are ignored. 3. Override · An external condition requires action outside the norm. · Operator and Program state requests are ignored. · Some examples of such conditions may include a module device fault, a downstream alarm condition, or a safety interlock, or other conditions that would prevent the module from performing its intended function. · The raM_Opr_CfgStateModel can be configured to transition to a specified state or continue normal operation when an Override condition exists.
